habitat_description:
Distributed across the lowlands of the Atlantic and Pacific from extreme south Texas and south Sonora to Costa Rica (Behler and King 1979; Conant and Collins 1998). 

Preferred habitat are areas of subhumid regions; known to seek shelter in the outer sheaths of banana trees, damp tree holes, underground, and under tree bark (Conant and Collins 1998). Found in dry, arid areas in the northern part of its range and contrastingly in humid areas along streams, trees, and canyons in the south from sea level to 1000m localities (Behler and King 1979). Adults are nocturnal and only active after rains while breeding will occur in small temporary pools. This species inhabits brushy and forested areas surrounding streams, roadside ditches, and resacas, but also atop of palm trees (Lanoo 2005)

Found under loose tree bark, tree holes, leaves of banana plants, bromeliads, heliconias, and in moist soil (Lannoo 2005)
